Restriction of oral intake of water for aspiration lung disease in children Primary aspiration of food and fluid can cause serious lung consequences in infants and children.
Treatment recommendations for children who have primary aspiration of thin fluids includes restriction of thin fluids and provision of thickened fluids.
Children often refuse to drink thickened fluids presenting a challenge for families to ensure that the child takes sufficient fluid.
Allowing children who have thin fluid aspiration to drink water may assist in providing enough fluid without endangering the lung .
This review found no evidence about drinking water in children with primary aspiration of thin fluids.